data.title: St. Michael Catholic Cemetery
data.text:
East Galena Township

Part 2

Go to Part 1

This cemetery was started by the parishioners in 1842. Previously all burials were either at Old City Cemetery in a consecrated area, or at one of the other Catholic cemeteries, such as Pilots Knob in East Galena Township or St. Marys in Vinegar Hill Township. In 1929 the St. Michael's Church took over the St. Mary's Catholic Cemetery at Vinegar Hill. St. Mary's Cemetery in West Galena Township did not open until 1856. One section of St. Michael's was converted into a newer burial ground by the moving of tombstones to a different point within the cemetery. Some say the current area has anywhere from one to three levels of burials already there. In the early 1900s a fire at the sexton's shed destroyed the records and equipment. The records are available from about 1912 only. St. Michael's Cemetery borders Route 20 and Bouthillier Street on the east side of the City of Galena. The following readings also include information from the sexton's records.

Our thanks to Marjorie Smith for transcribing and contributing this material to the Jo Daviess USGenWeb site.
